WATCH this morning's hit: https://t.co/lhYhzU4Yqe

I didn't protest (and I'm sure you didn't either) for 8 years just to get Obamacare Lite. This bill is a swamp monster. I've discussed it at length in great detail on air (and hitting it again today). You cannot fix Obamacare. That's what this bill is attempting to do. You either let Obamacare fail or you repeal it. Those are the options (we also aren't limited to reconciliation, I'm fully aware of this process and the limitations under which current action is placed, but it's irrelevant in repeal discussion). 

- Medicaid expansion is capped, somewhat.
- Individual penalty paid to insurance companies for not buying their products still exists
- We're still subsidizing other people's health care
- The same Obamacare regulatory structure is in place but any and all method to control spending has been removed.

Alternatively, the repeal bill intro'd in 2015 would fund Ocare for 2 years while a real, market-based replacement was introduced. 

GOP, to their credit, introduced numerous plans from 2008 - 2010, none of which saw the light of day because Democrat leadership wouldn't allow it. 

I said this morning on Fox that this bill is an insult to all the hardworking Americans who are paying double and triple premiums, who lost their care, or who can't even get care anymore. Obamacare in its mid-collapse. Insurers are fleeing the market place exchanges, it's flailing. The GOP is trying to take ownership with this bill. They're trying to transfer legacy of this bill from Obama to Trump. 

I'd rather GOP let Obamacare fail (which it is currently) and start over than to pass this. It's not a repeal and replace. It's a tinker. I'll repeat: Obamacare cannot be saved, it cannot be tinkered with. It's either repeal or fail, GOP owns or doesn't own. "Tinkering" with it and other such ideas is exactly why Trump won. 

This isn't being a "purist." That's partisan rhetoric used by people who want you to falsely believe that you have no other choices. 

It's being a realist. 

I think Trump knows what's up -- check out my Tweet:
https://twitter.com/DLoesch/status/840231842020245504

GOP needs the messaging to match that of POTUS. If they step it up, they will win, we will win. 

Put the heat on your representatives, your senators. Trump will back them and he'll negotiate. He's already floating them an out. All they have to do is take it.

Thoughts on President Trump's #JointSession address (transcript linked):

1) This was Trump's best speech of his political career.

2) I loved how he placed the blame for criminal violence on the criminals, not law-abiding gun owners. 

3) He began by honoring Black History Month, condemned attacks on Jewish cemeteries and synagogues. 

4) "RADICAL. ISLAMIC. TERRORISM." 

5) He backed the blue, hard. 

6) I did not like the proposed spending on infrastructure. Where is fuel tax $ going? We already granted congress a trillion (literally) dollars on this and it went to slush funds and other. Intrigued by the inclusion of "private and public" funding. 

7) 100% against the paid family leave proposal. Paid for by whom? We are not in the business of mandating that businesses provide something like this simply for existing. It's Obamacare logic. I'm more strongly opposed to this than anything else he's said -- at least the infrastructure has Constitutional basis (Article 1 Section 8). Paid family leave is not what we do. Conserve individual sovereignty. 

8) Trump beautifully honored Carryn Owens, Ryan Owens' widow. Before any drive-bys smart off -- get it straight: This was a mission already in the works before the final vote. If you think that special ops can be on the ground and a mission and intel gathering effort of that sort can be greenlit in a few days after he is elected, you're a clueless partisan who needs to not disrespect the loss of a warrior to further a baseless political agenda. Owens received several standing ovations. My heart broke for her and I just wanted to hug her. God bless their family. 

All the women in white (protesting for "women's rights" or some schtick) should get a long look at Carryn Owens, the face of strength and real sacrifice. 

9) "My job is not to represent the world. My job is to represent the United States of America."  BINGO. 

10) Refugee note: "Only longterm solution for these humanitarian disasters is to create the conditions where displaced persons can safely return home."

11) "The time for trivial fights is behind us." 
Some people need this note. Choose to divide or unite. 
Also -- if you're in it just to fight other conservatives over the primary, join the left, because you're already doing their bidding. #RealTalk 

12) Democrats declined to applaud jobs and school choice showing the rural and urban communities who leaned Trump exactly why they were right to do so. 

Like I said, best speech Trump has ever given. 

Interesting response from the old dude Democrat trying to make a grab for the blue collar base Trump stole during the election. Democrats sold out blue dogs and blue collars for identity politics. That blue collar demo is still delivering elections. Dems miscalculated.

Heck yes I'm watching the Oscars. I love movies more than most there might hate my political beliefs. Also because politics is DOWNSTREAM from pop culture. It never made sense to me to take my ball and go home, to cede the battlefield just because not enough may think like me. You'll never win if you only preach to the choir and you'll never know how people outside of the choir think unless you engage them. I like to see trends, who gets political, who doesn't, tone, etc etc. It may not be your bag, but it's mine. I don't do boycotts and I will never stop loving arts and entertainment just because I'm a conservative! Also it's ok to unclench your butt sometimes and ENJOY LIFE! I'm not politics 24-7 and have interests outside of news. /RequisiteExplainer 

#Oscars observations so far:

- Kirsten Dunst has THE best look. Dior, black, simple.

- I wish Justin Timberlake was hosting. He's a phenomenal performer. Kimmel sucks.

- The Rock wore a velvet tux. I've never seen a velvet jacket on anyone with biceps. 

- Auli'i Cravalho (Moana) was amazing! Vocal skill, dress, hair, all A+++++

- Only slightly politically annoying. Nothing over the top yet.

- Love love love Viola Davis, disagree that acting is the only profession that celebrates life, though.

- Asghar Farhadi wins Best Foreign Language film, uses his speech to insult the country hosting the event that just gave him an award. (I just totally triggered progressive Twitter with this remark, lol.)

- I'm on the fence re Leslie Mann's dress: Beauty and the Beast or Pile O' Mustard?

- DENZEL WAS ROBBED.

- Emma Stone was wearing a Planned Parenthood pin. I take back liking her as a person.

- Hollywood almost awarded itself for La La Land and after a big, embarrassing mistake at an awards show for editing, directing, etc, Moonlight was correctly awarded. Geez.

- Thank you to the winners + presenters for being mostly cool & not alienating people who want to like your work w/o political condescension.

I've rather enjoyed watching the campus crusades, though he's said some things before that give me pause. But this? I have sons. I'm draconian on punishment for child abusers (death penalty). He essentially says that he himself was a victim (heartbreaking) and I think this shapes his perspective. Yes, consent is important -- physical and emotional maturation do not happen simultaneously. 
However, 13 and 14 year-olds cannot be "predators" (ages mentioned in one of the videos). I can't imagine anyone in their right mind viewing a 13 year-old as such. One of my children is 12. He is absolutely unable to consent to such a thing and I would render someone carried by six if so. Age of consent isn't "arbitrary," it exists for a reason. You can watch these yourselves to form your own conclusion. 

All I know is that such attitudes from people like Lena Dunham, or actions like those of Salon, that has a regular series where they're trying to mainstream pederasty, are intolerable. It's the ultimate war on boys, war on men (all children!) to suggest that the age of consent is debatable because a personal experience has caused one to see some children as "predators." Many times victims are convinced that they are "predators" by their abuser. I also don't care how mature anyone thinks they are or were at 13, 14, 15, they are not emotionally mature enough for an adult (read as abusive, exploitative) "relationship" and I simply want to wring the neck of any abuser who convinced a victim otherwise against their own best interest (i.e. the admission in one of the videos).

status_message:
A rant. 

READ ALL OF IT.

I am SICKENED by this:
http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/04/us/chicago-facebook-live-beating/

Look, Trump was NOT my primary candidate, but the primary and general election are OVER. 
(There was money to be made by division grifters who claimed to speak for me, but I digress.)

I called this over a year ago when I wrote "Flyover Nation." It's WHY I wrote this book. 

There are many flyover friends, many of my family members from the heartland, who voted for Trump. They are good people. They are not "racists/bigots/Nazis." One of my elderly family members voted for Trump. After losing access to their specialist, this relative was tired of their concerns met with nothing more than lectures about identity politics. 

These people, flyover people, have been stereotyped, mocked, and ridiculed my entire life. We are the first people to feel the burn of the coasts's attack on culture and Washington's bad policies. These are people who watched as Democrats peddled away jobs through burdensome corporate regulations, they watched as Hillary Clinton told them she wanted to ruin their industries, take away their jobs and impoverish their families: "We're going to put a lot of coal miners and coal companies out of business." 
Who in the hell do you think works in that industry? It's populated by working class moms and dads. 

As these folks struggled to keep employed, lights on, and food on the table they were lectured by the left about bathrooms, and pronouns. As they lost their health insurance they were told by the left that their realized fears were made up stories. They watch programming mostly packaged by media entities on the coasts who don't care if flyover is burning or flooding, like in Tennessee, so long as it's not California or New Jersey. Someone, I can't recall whom, for proper attribution, but someone I read recently put it brilliantly: These people felt like outsiders looking in, their faces pressed against the glass, wondering when they were going to get their piece of improvement. When were they going to win? Where was their hope? 

A disproportionate amount (cited in my book in its own chapter) of our military men and women, come from these people, are these people, are flyover nation.

These folks got tired of hearing about how Hillary Clinton's inability to sell America on her policies was somehow THEIR fault. How DARE you impugn the character of these people when it was YOUR ideology that failed these people, YOUR policies that wouldn't sell. 

They were good enough to vote TWICE for Bill Clinton, but after they've been stepped on, walked over, and ignored for the the last eight-plus years they're suddenly "racists" and "Nazis" because they chose to gamble their vote on the HOPE of something different? Because they don't vote how YOU want them to, suddenly these people are "bigots/sexists/racists/Nazis?" What were they when they SUPPORTED your politicians, your policies, your ideology? 

It's easier to smear people than to admit that your policies sucked and you were wrong. These people pushing this ridiculousness claim to care SO MUCH for the country that they're willing to promote false narratives that drive division and create the atmosphere which create incidents like the sickening story linked above. 

If you're pushing this, SHAME on you. YOU did this, not Trump, not his supporters. YOU are part of this problem.

Everybody mad about Beyonce at the CMAs. Her song, "Daddy Lessons" is a track from her last album literally on defensive gun use (leave it to me). I'm all for someone singing about protecting themselves with a gun -- and it wasn't in an ironic fashion. She's Texan. Texans don't play with that. Her BLM/police stance has earned her MUCH deserved criticism but I'm not jumping on her for this particular track or the message behind it, and I don't feel that others should also. Also, for some asking why she performed this at the CMAs, have they heard her album? It was produced very Rick-Rubin-esque; Jack White even produced a track. The song she performed at the CMAs is an easy cross-over track with an appealing subject for this audience. Ray Charles is in the Country Music Hall of Fame. Chris Stapleton is a mix of country, blues, and soul. Don't forget Charlie Pride, either. Many crossovers, many styles. In a time of depressing division, I'm happy for the crossovers, even if it was with the universally annoying Dixie Chicks and that loudmouth Natalie Maines, lol.

(For the record, I like outlaw country -- and also metal and punk -- like Waylon, Jesse, Willie, Bocephus, etc!)

If you haven't heard, pay attention to the proposed new regulations from the Obama admin that would treat gunsmiths (like the one that lightened my trigger on my old S&W revolver) the same as manufacturers. This means they would have to pay the same exorbitant fee$ that mass-producing entities pay -- effectively putting them out of business as most are small mom and pop shops. It's exactly like treating your neighborhood car mechanic like he's Ford, the mass-producing automobile manufacturer. Mass production is what makes a manufacturer, yet that term is being redefined for the sake of further restrictions on 2A. My friend Bob Owens has a great write-up of the nitty gritty here:

status_message:
Blurry firework video time! Watched pre-Fourth fireworks from a restaurant parking lot. Noticed a little old man walking out with his wife. He took absolutely zero notice of the fireworks, as if it was an everyday thing to him. As he passed I noticed part of his hat I could see read TERAN in big gold embroidery -- like my grandpa's WWII hat did. My youngest was already on it though. By the time this vet passed and I realized what war he was from my little guy darted in between Chris and I and made a beeline for this old veteran before we could say anything. I saw our little guy stick out his hand to the old man who bent down shook his, and they talked for a bit. Then the vet extended his hand again slowly, deliberately, and clasped Ewan's and shook it confidently, with purpose, only the way a vet can. Ewan walked back over and didn't say a word. 

"So what did he say?" I asked. 

"Well I thanked him for his service," he said matter-of-factly. "He is a WWII vet, a marine," he replied. "I remember how you said there weren't many WWII veterans around and all the ones we knew, like my great-grandpas, were dead. He told me that when I'm in school learning about WWII to raise my hand and tell him that I know a marine who served in the South Pacific." üôå‚ù§Ô∏èüá∫üá∏ #myboy

So #UnderTheGun director Stephanie Soechtig may have violated federal law -- 18 U.S.C 922(a)(3): http://www.ammoland.com/2016/06/under-the-gun-director-soechtig-confesses-to-federal-crimes/#axzz4AU3uuKmW

"The Gun Control Act of 1968 (GCA), Title 18, United States Code (U.S.C.), Chapter 44, imposes Federal controls on FFLs who transfer firearms in interstate commerce. Section 922(a)(2) makes it unlawful for an FFL to ship or transport in interstate or foreign commerce any firearm to a person other than an FFL. Section 922(b)(3) makes it unlawful for an FFL to sell or deliver a firearm to a person he or she knows does not reside in the State in which the FFL's place of business is located." - https://www.atf.gov/file/55481/download

Note: When John Belton wrote to the Continental Congress about his first automatic weapon, they wanted it for Washington's army ‚Ä¶

The Founders could have forced Belton to provide, or even banned his automatic weaponry. They did neither ...

The argument that the Founders meant only muskets should embarrass any historical illiterate who makes the argument.

According to Belton's spring 1777 letters to congress (and the Founders's subsequent correspondence with each other over it) ...

The only thing stopping them from acquiring Belton's emerging tech was cost. And note, his wasn't the only one who increase the RPM.

You are invited to the 
July Wendy P. McCaw

and her best selling book, 
Hands Off My Gun.

Dana Loesch hosts her award-winning, nationally syndicated daily radio show, The Dana Show: The Conservative Alternative from Dallas, Texas where she also hosts "Dana" on TheBlaze television network. Dana appears regularly on Fox News, ABC, CNN, among others, and has co-hosted on "The View." She describes herself as a "conservatarian."

Dana's original brand of young, punk-rock, conservative irreverence has found a fast-growing audience in multiple mediums. Dana is listed in the top 40 of Talkers Magazine's top 100 "heavy hitters" and was named Missouri's #1 Radio Personality in 2014. A former award-winning newspaper columnist (and notable blogger since 2001), Dana was ranked as one of the top 16 most powerful mothers online by Neilsen and one of the top 30 Under 30 according to the St. Louis Business Journal. Dana was the 2012 winner of Accuracy In Media's Grassroots Journalism award as well as the inaugural Breitbart Spirit Award. Dana was one of the original Breitbart editors selected by her late friend and mentor, Andrew Breitbart, to head what was BigJournalism.com and helped break the Anthony Weiner scandal before departing in 2012. Her Best Selling book on gun control, Hands Off My Gun: Defeating the Plot to Disarm America is on shelves now and is turning the tide in the gun debate. Mark Levin wrote of her book that it, "Obliterates every baseless argument made against the Second Amendment." Sean Hannity quipped, "Buy this book before someone tries to ban it." Michelle Malkin states, "WARNING: This book is explosive! Mother, wife, New Media warrior and political sharpshooter Dana Loesch confronts the ultimate war on women: gun control."

Dana co-founded the tea party movement in St. Louis and speaks regularly on the subject of new media, gun control, anti-feminism, and grassroots.

A native Missourian, she and her family now live in Texas.
